    "ane_backdrop": "Oath-taking in the Ancient Near East was a sacred, legally binding act that invoked divine witnesses and carried severe penalties for violation. In Mesopotamian treaty texts, gods swore by their own names or by cosmic elements (heaven, earth, mountains) to guarantee treaty terms. The Atrahasis Epic and Gilgamesh Epic both feature divine oaths after catastrophic floods — in Atrahasis, the goddess Ishtar swears by her lapis lazuli necklace never to forget the flood days. Genesis 9:8-17 presents God's covenant with Noah as a unilateral oath: God binds himself without requiring human performance. The 'sign in the heaven' (the rainbow/bow) is both memorial and weapon laid down — in ANE iconography, the divine bow was a weapon of judgment. By hanging his bow in the clouds, God symbolically declares the war against creation is over. 1 Enoch 55 preserves this tradition while connecting it to eschatological themes.",
    
