    "divine_council_note": "The phrase 'Head of Days' (used here and in 1 Enoch 46-47) is a title for God emphasizing his eternal sovereignty and role as presiding judge over the divine council. The oath-taking described in 55:2 has cosmic legal force: when the Head of Days swears by his own name, he invokes the highest possible authority. This reflects the ancient understanding that divine oaths were witnessed by the council — Job 38:7 says the 'sons of God' (b'nei elohim) sang at creation, and Psalm 89:7 describes God as 'awesome in the council of the holy ones.' The Noahic covenant is thus not merely a promise to humanity but a decree issued in the divine court, binding on all parties. The 'sign in heaven' (rainbow) serves as a perpetual witness, visible to both earthly and heavenly realms, of God's sworn commitment.",
    
