        {
            "heading": "The Divine Repentance — Anthropomorphic Language (55:1-2)",
            "body": "[C] 1 Enoch 55 opens with striking language: 'the Head of Days repented and said: In vain have I destroyed all who dwell on the earth.'' This echoes Genesis 6:6-7, where God 'regretted' (nacham) making humanity. <strong>Does God actually change his mind?</strong> [B] Classical theology distinguishes between God's immutable nature and his relational responses to human action. The Hebrew nacham (and its Greek equivalent metanoeō in LXX) can mean 'to be grieved' or 'to relent' — it's anthropopathic language describing God's emotional response in terms humans can understand.<br><br>[A] Genesis 8:21 records God's internal resolution: 'I will never again curse the ground because of man... neither will I ever again strike down every living creature.' This is not a change in God's character but a change in his <em>mode of dealing</em> with human sin. The flood was a one-time reset; henceforth judgment will be delayed until the eschaton.<br><br>[C] The Enochic tradition interprets this as God recognizing that the destruction was 'in vain' (mataia) — not because it was unjustified (the generation was utterly corrupt) but because human sinfulness would persist. The solution isn't repeated global destruction but the establishment of covenant structures (law, priesthood, ultimately Messiah) to manage sin until final judgment. [B] This reading is supported by Romans 3:25-26, where Paul says God passed over former sins 'in his divine forbearance' — the Noahic covenant inaugurated the age of forbearance."
