            "heading": "The Oath by the Great Name — Covenant Mechanics (55:2)",
            "body": "[C] 'He swore by His great name' — in ancient oath-taking, the swearer invoked a higher authority as witness and guarantor. [A] But God has no higher authority (Hebrews 6:13), so he swears by himself, by his own name (YHWH). This makes the oath absolutely binding and irrevocable. [B] In Ancient Near Eastern treaty language, self-maledictory oaths included curses the swearer called down on himself if he violated the oath. When God swears by his name, he stakes his own reputation and character on keeping the promise.<br><br>[A] Isaiah 54:9 directly references this: 'This is like the days of Noah to me: as I swore that the waters of Noah should no more go over the earth, so I have sworn that I will not be angry with you, and will not rebuke you.' God appeals to the Noahic oath as the paradigm of his covenant faithfulness. [B] The structure is: <em>Just as</em> I kept my oath to Noah (never again a global flood), <em>so</em> I will keep my oath to Israel (never again total rejection).<br><br>[C] 1 Enoch 55 places this oath in the context of eschatological judgment, suggesting that the 'never again by water' promise implicitly includes 'but judgment will come by other means.' [A] 2 Peter 3:5-7 makes this explicit: the world that perished by water is now 'reserved for fire, being kept until the day of judgment.' The Noahic covenant doesn't eliminate judgment; it changes the <em>timing</em> and <em>method</em>."
        },
        {
            "heading": "The Sign in Heaven — The Rainbow as Legal Witness (55:2)",
            "body": "[A] Genesis 9:12-17 identifies the 'sign' as the rainbow (qesheth, also meaning 'bow' as in weapon). God says, 'When I bring clouds over the earth and the bow is seen in the clouds, I will remember my covenant.' [B] The language is covenantal-legal: the rainbow functions as a <em>visible reminder</em> to God himself (anthropomorphically) and as a <em>witness</em> to creation that the covenant is in force. Ancient treaties were often accompanied by physical monuments or signs that served as perpetual witnesses (cf. Joshua 24:27, the stone that 'heard' God's words).<br><br>[C] In Ancient Near Eastern iconography, the divine bow was a weapon of storm gods (Marduk, Baal). By 'setting his bow in the clouds,' God symbolically <em>lays down his weapon</em>. The war against creation is over. The bow now points upward (toward heaven) rather than downward (toward earth), indicating that God has sheathed his judgment. [B] This imagery resonates with Habakkuk 3:9-11, where God's bow is drawn in theophanic judgment, and Psalm 7:12-13, where God 'bends his bow' against the wicked.<br><br>[C] 1 Enoch 55's reference to the 'sign in heaven' may also evoke the eschatological 'sign of the Son of Man in heaven' (Matthew 24:30). Just as the rainbow signaled the end of water judgment and the beginning of the covenant age, the eschatological sign will mark the end of the age of forbearance and the beginning of final judgment. [B] The rainbow thus becomes a <em>type</em> of the eschatological sign — both are heavenly, visible, and covenant-related."
        },
        {
            "heading": "Springs of Water That Do Not Fail — Reversal of Judgment (55:3)",
            "body": "[C] 1 Enoch 55:3 (in some manuscripts) refers to 'springs of water' that will sustain the righteous and never fail. This is a profound reversal motif: the waters that once destroyed (mabbul, the flood) are transformed into waters that give life. [B] This parallels the Exodus pattern, where the Red Sea waters destroy Egypt but save Israel, and the bitter waters of Marah are made sweet (Exodus 15:22-25).<br><br>[A] Isaiah 41:17-18 promises that God will open 'rivers on the bare heights, and fountains in the midst of the valleys' for the thirsty. [A] Isaiah 58:11 says, 'You shall be like a watered garden, like a spring of water, whose waters do not fail.' [B] The 'unfailing springs' become a metaphor for God's perpetual provision for the faithful. [C] In Enochic eschatology, this provision is not merely physical but spiritual — access to divine wisdom, righteousness, and ultimately resurrection life.<br><br>[A] Jesus picks up this imagery in John 4:14: 'Whoever drinks of the water that I will give him will never be thirsty again. The water that I will give him will become in him a spring of water welling up to eternal life.' [B] And in John 7:37-39, Jesus stands during the Feast of Tabernacles (which commemorates wilderness provision) and declares, 'If anyone thirsts, let him come to me and drink... Out of his heart will flow rivers of living water' — which John interprets as the Holy Spirit. [C] The Enochic 'springs that do not fail' find their ultimate fulfillment in the eschatological river of Revelation 22:1, flowing from the throne of God and the Lamb."
        },
