            "heading": "The Righteous and the Elect — Continuity with Noahic Paradigm (55:4)",
            "body": "[C] 1 Enoch 55:4 shifts to the vindication of 'the righteous and the elect,' using terminology consistent throughout the Parables (chapters 37-71). The connection to Noah is implicit but clear: <strong>just as Noah was righteous in his generation and was saved through judgment, so the elect will be preserved through the final judgment.</strong> [A] Genesis 6:9 says, 'Noah was a righteous man, blameless in his generation. Noah walked with God.' [A] Ezekiel 14:14, 20 lists Noah alongside Daniel and Job as exemplars of righteousness who could deliver only themselves by their righteousness in a time of judgment.<br><br>[B] The Noahic pattern establishes a template: <em>global corruption → remnant preserved → covenant renewal</em>. [C] The Enochic Parables apply this template eschatologically: the present age is corrupt (dominated by kings, mighty ones, and the fallen Watchers' legacy), but the elect will be preserved and will inherit the renewed earth. [A] Jesus uses Noahic typology in Matthew 24:37-39: 'As were the days of Noah, so will be the coming of the Son of Man. For as in those days before the flood they were eating and drinking... until the flood came and swept them all away, so will be the coming of the Son of Man.' [B] The point is not the specific sins but the <em>obliviousness to impending judgment</em> and the <em>sudden, inescapable nature</em> of that judgment.<br><br>[C] 1 Enoch 55 thus functions as a hinge chapter: it looks back to the Noahic covenant (God's oath after water judgment) and forward to the final judgment (when the elect will be vindicated). The 'springs of water' that sustained Noah's family through the flood become a symbol of the eternal life that will sustain the righteous in the age to come."
