            "heading": "Theological Synthesis — The Oath as Eschatological Framework",
            "body": "[B] The Noahic covenant establishes the <em>stability of the present age</em>. Genesis 8:22 promises, 'While the earth remains, seedtime and harvest, cold and heat, summer and winter, day and night, shall not cease.' This is not an eternal promise (the earth will not remain forever) but a <em>provisional guarantee</em> that the natural order will function reliably until the eschaton. [A] 2 Peter 3:10 clarifies the terminus: 'The day of the Lord will come like a thief, and then the heavens will pass away with a roar, and the heavenly bodies will be burned up and dissolved, and the earth and the works that are done on it will be exposed.'<br><br>[C] 1 Enoch 55's placement in the Parables suggests that the Noahic oath is not merely about flood prevention but about <em>the structure of the interim age</em>. God has bound himself not to destroy the earth prematurely, allowing time for the full number of the elect to be gathered (cf. Romans 11:25, Revelation 6:11). [B] The oath creates a legal framework within which human history unfolds: God will judge, but not yet; he will destroy evil, but not until the appointed time; he will vindicate the righteous, but they must endure the present age.<br><br>[A] Romans 2:4 asks, 'Do you presume on the riches of his kindness and forbearance and patience, not knowing that God's kindness is meant to lead you to repentance?' [B] The Noahic covenant's 'never again by water' is an expression of divine patience, not indifference. The delay of judgment is purposeful. [C] The Enochic tradition understood this: the oath to Noah guarantees that the present corrupt age will continue <em>until</em> the Son of Man appears, the elect are vindicated, and the wicked face final judgment. The rainbow is both a comfort (judgment is restrained) and a warning (judgment is certain, only delayed)."
